In this article, we'll be comparing the performance of Synnax to two other leading
time-series databases: [TimescaleDB](https://www.timescale.com/) and [InfluxDB](https://www.influxdata.com/index/).

Performance is one of many factors to consider when evaluating the time-series 
database for your use case: scalability, reliability, and query language are also important 
to consider. Timescale, Influx, and Synnax all have their strengths and weaknesses. 

Synnax is specifically built for storing and streaming hardware sensor data. Our 
database excels at read and write throughput for low cardinality time series workloads.

<Note.Note variant="info">
Performance benchmarks are often controversial, as companies choose specific workloads
optimized for their database architecture. In our evaluation, we'll be cherry picking
a scenario as well. Our goal is to prove that **Synnax is by far the fastest data storage & 
streaming solution for high-speed hardware sensor data.** 
</Note.Note>

## Test Summary

We'll have two [channels](/reference/concepts/channels) (tags in InfluxDB, columns in TimescaleDB).
One channel (`time`) will hold `int64` nanosecond timestamps, and the other channel
(`value`) will hold `float32` sensor values. Combined, all rows will total just under
11GB of data.

There will be two parts to our test:

1. **Insertion**: We'll insert one billion rows of data into each database in chunks
of 100,000 rows.
2. **Read**: We'll read back all one billion rows in chunks of 100,000 rows.
